aa(lp42
VWell, now we know that autism is this disruption,
p43
aVthe disruption of this resonance that I am telling you about.
p44
aVThese are survival skills.
p45
aVThese are survival skills that we inherited
p46
aVover many, many hundreds of thousands of years of evolution.
p47
aa(lp48
VYou see, babies are born in a state of utter fragility.
p49
aVWithout the caregiver, they wouldn't survive,
p50
aVso it stands to reason that nature would endow them
p51
aVwith these mechanisms of survival.
p52
aVThey orient to the caregiver.
p53
aVFrom the first days and weeks of life,
p54
aVbabies prefer to hear human sounds,
p55
aVrather than just sounds in the environment.
p56
aVThey prefer to look at people rather than at things,
p57
aVand even as they're looking at people, they look at people's eyes,
p58
aVbecause the eye is the window to the other person's experiences,
p59
aVso much so that they even prefer to look at people
p60
aVwho are looking at them rather than people who are looking away.
p61
aVWell, they orient to the caregiver.
p62
aVThe caregiver seeks the baby.
p63
aVAnd it's out of this mutually reinforcing choreography
p64
aVthat a lot that is of importance to the emergence of mind \u2014
p65
aVthe social mind, the social brain \u2014 depends on.
p66
aa(lp67
VWe always think about autism
p68
aVas something that happens later on in life.
p69
aVIt doesn't; it begins with the beginning of life.
p70
aVAs babies engage with caregivers, they soon realize that, well,
p71
aVthere is something between the ears that is very important \u2014
p72
aVit's invisible, you can't see it, but it's really critical.
p73
aVAnd that thing is called attention.
p74
aVAnd they learn soon enough,
p75
aVeven before they can utter one word,
p76
aVthat they can take that attention and move somewhere
p77
aVin order to get things they want.
p78
aVThey also learn to follow other people's gazes,
p79
aVbecause whatever people are looking at is what they are thinking about.
p80
aVAnd soon enough, they start to learn about the meaning of things,
p81
aVbecause when somebody is looking at something
p82
aVor somebody is pointing at something,
p83
aVthey're not just getting a directional cue.
p84
aVThey are getting the other person's meaning of that thing,
p85
aVthe attitude.
p86
aVAnd soon enough, they start building this body of meanings,
p87
aVbut meanings that were acquired within the realm of social interaction.
p88
aVThose are meanings that are acquired
p89
aVas part of their shared experiences with others.
