aa(lp146
VWell, autism is the most strongly genetic condition
p147
aVof all developmental disorders.
p148
aVAnd it's a brain disorder.
p149
aVIt's a disorder that begins much prior to the time
p150
aVthat the child is born.
p151
aVWe now know that there is a very broad spectrum of autism.
p152
aVThere are those individuals who are profoundly intellectually disabled
p153
aVbut there are those that are gifted.
p154
aVThere are those individuals who don't talk at all;
p155
aVthere are those individuals who talk too much.
p156
aVThere are those individuals that if you observe them in their school,
p157
aVyou see them running the periphery fence all the school day if you let them,
p158
aVto those individuals who cannot stop coming to you
p159
aVand trying to engage you repeatedly, relentlessly,
p160
aVbut often in an awkward fashion,
p161
aVwithout that immediate resonance.
p162
aa(lp163
VWell, this is much more prevalent than we thought at the time.
p164
aVWhen I started in this field,
p165
aVwe thought there were four individuals with autism per 10,000 \u2014
p166
aVa very rare condition.
p167
aVWell, now we know it's more like one in 100.
p168
aVThere are millions of individuals with autism all around us.
p169
aa(lp170
VThe societal cost of this condition is huge,
p171
aVin the US alone, maybe 35 to 80 billion dollars.
p172
aVAnd you know what?
p173
aVMost of those funds are associated with adolescents and particularly adults
p174
aVwho are severely disabled,
p175
aVindividuals who need wraparound services \u2014
p176
aVservices that are very, very intensive.
p177
aVAnd those services can cost in excess of 60,000 to 80,000 dollars a year.
p178
aVThose are individuals who did not benefit from early treatment,
p179
aVbecause now we know that autism creates itself
p180
aVas individuals diverge in that pathway of learning that I mentioned to you.
p181
aVWere we to be able to identify this condition
p182
aVat an earlier point, and intervene and treat \u2014
p183
aVI can tell you, this has been probably something that has changed my life
p184
aVin the past 10 years,
p185
aVthis notion that we can absolutely attenuate this condition.
p186
aVAlso, we have a window of opportunity,
p187
aVbecause the brain is malleable for just so long,
p188
aVand that window of opportunity happens in the first three years of life.
p189
aVIt's not that that window closes; it doesn't.
p190
aVBut it diminishes considerably.
p191
aVAnd yet, the median age of diagnosis in this country
p192
aVis still about five years,
p193
aVand in disadvantaged populations,
p194
aVthe populations that don't have access to clinical services,
p195
aVrural populations, minorities,
p196
aVthe age of diagnosis is later still,
p197
aVwhich is almost as if I were to tell you
p198
aVthat we are condemning those communities to have individuals with autism
p199
aVwhose condition is going to be more severe.
p200
aVSo I feel that we have a bioethical imperative.
p201
aVThe science is there.
p202
aVBut no science is of relevance
p203
aVif it doesn't have an impact on the community.
p204
aVAnd we just can't afford that missed opportunity,
p205
aVbecause children with autism become adults with autism.
p206
aVAnd we feel that those things we can do
p207
aVfor these children, for those families, early on,
p208
aVwill have lifetime consequences \u2014
p209
aVfor the child, for the family, and for the community at large.
p210
aVSo this is our view of autism.
