aa(lp212
VThere are over a hundred genes that are associated with autism.
p213
aVIn fact, we believe there are going to be
p214
aVsomething between 300 and 600 genes associated with autism,
p215
aVand genetic anomalies, much more than just genes.
p216
aVAnd we actually have a bit of a question here,
p217
aVbecause if there are so many different causes of autism,
p218
aVhow do you go from those liabilities to the actual syndrome?
p219
aVBecause people like myself,
p220
aVwhen we walk into a playroom,
p221
aVwe recognize a child as having autism.
p222
aVSo how do you go from multiple causes
p223
aVto a syndrome that has some homogeneity?
p224
aVAnd the answer is what lies in between,
p225
aVwhich is development.
p226
aVAnd in fact, we are very interested in those first two years of life,
p227
aVbecause those liabilities don't necessarily convert into autism.
p228
aVAutism creates itself.
p229
aVWere we to be able to intervene during those years of life,
p230
aVwe might attenuate for some, and God knows, maybe even prevent for others.
p231
aa(lp232
VSo how do we do that?
p233
aVHow do we enter that feeling of resonance,
p234
aVhow do we enter another person's being?
p235
aVI remember when I interacted with that 15-month-old,
p236
aVthe thing that came to my mind was,
p237
aV"How do you come into her world?
p238
aVIs she thinking about me? Is she thinking about others?"
p239
aVWell, it's hard to do that,
p240
aVso we had to create the technologies.
p241
aVWe had to basically step inside a body.
p242
aVWe had to see the world through her eyes.
p243
aa(lp244
VAnd so in the past many years,
p245
aVwe've been building these new technologies
p246
aVthat are based on eye tracking.
p247
aVWe can see, moment by moment, what children are engaging with.
p248
aVThis is my colleague, Warren Jones,
p249
aVwith whom we've been building these methods, these studies,
p250
aVfor the past 12 years.
p251
aVAnd you see there a happy five-month-old,
p252
aVa five-month little boy who is going to watch things
p253
aVthat are brought from his world:
p254
aVhis mom, the caregiver,
p255
aVbut also experiences that he would have were he to be in his daycare.
p256
aVWhat we want is to embrace that world and bring it into our laboratory,
p257
aVbut in order for us to do that,
p258
aVwe had to create these very sophisticated measures,
p259
aVmeasures of how people, how little babies,
p260
aVhow newborns, engage with the world, moment by moment.
p261
aVWhat is important and what is not.
